🛡️ Explainable Ransomware Detection using Machine Learning (XAI)
🚀 Project Overview

This project presents a Machine Learning–based ransomware detection system enhanced with Explainable AI (XAI) techniques to improve transparency, trust, and decision-making.

Unlike traditional black-box models, this system not only detects ransomware but also provides clear explanations behind every prediction.

🔍 What makes it different?
Identifies whether a file/process is malicious or benign
Explains why a prediction was made
Highlights key contributing features
Provides actionable counterfactual insights
🎯 Problem Statement

Ransomware is one of the most dangerous cybersecurity threats today. However, conventional detection systems face major limitations:

❌ Lack of interpretability
❌ No insight into model decisions
❌ Low trust among security analysts

This project solves these issues by combining:

Machine Learning + Explainability + Counterfactual Reasoning

💡 Proposed Solution

A complete end-to-end pipeline that includes:

Data → Preprocessing → Model Training → Evaluation → Explainability → Insights
Key Components:
Data preprocessing & balancing
Model training using multiple algorithms
Performance evaluation with critical metrics
Explainability using XAI techniques
Counterfactual analysis for decision improvement
🧠 Features
🔍 Ransomware Classification

Classifies input into:

Ransomware
Benign
🤖 Machine Learning Models
Random Forest (Primary Model)
Decision Tree
Logistic Regression
Naive Bayes
📊 Model Evaluation Metrics
Accuracy
Precision
Recall ⭐ (most important)
F1-Score

⚠️ High recall is prioritized to minimize missed ransomware attacks.

🧠 Explainable AI (XAI)
✅ SHAP (SHapley Additive Explanations)
Global feature importance
Contribution of each feature to predictions
✅ LIME (Local Interpretable Model-Agnostic Explanations)
Explains individual predictions
Shows feature impact for a specific sample
🔥 Counterfactual Explanations (DiCE)
Generates “what-if” scenarios
Suggests minimal changes to alter predictions

Example Insight:

Reducing API call frequency may change classification from ransomware → benign

